column17: A passenger plane that departed from a Malta airport bound for Istanbul, but diverted to Cologne, Germany
column18: 6/9/1997: Two Turkish men hijacked an Air Malta passenger flight leaving from an airport in Malta bound for Istanbul.  One of the hijackers had fake explosives strapped to his chest; he threatened to blow up the plane unless it was rerouted to Cologne, Germany.  In addition, the hijackers demanded the release of Mehmet Ali Agca, a Turkish man who was in prison in Italy for attempting to assassinate Pope John Paul in 1981.  The assailants also requested an interview with a television station.  After landing in Cologne, the two hijackers allowed five of the 80 passengers and crew to deplane.   The two men eventually surrendered.
